  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">CIMI Tefe - Resistance of indigenous peoples in Medio Rio Solimoes</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to strengthen indigenous grassroots leaders, organisations and associations in Brazil so they can independently defend their constitutional rights.

The indigenous peoples living in Medio Rio Solimoes live relatively uncontacted and although they have had their lands officially demarcated they are still experiencing land threats and conflicts from external invaders (such as farmers, loggers, and miners). They lack adequate and culturally relevant education and health provision in their lands, and are experiencing food insecurity due to climate change. 

CIMI &#x2013; Indigenist Missionary Council of the Brazilian Bishops Conference, works through indigenous organisations and associations, undertaking training to stimulate sustainable agricultural production and income generation, mobilising communities to advocate for their rights, public policies and against legal amendments that adversely affect them, and raising awareness of rights violations amongst governmental authorities and the general public. 

The four key outcomes are: 
- Indigenous peoples are engaged on indigenous rights, social control, land management, gender and climate change.
- Indigenous people increase their knowledge of governmental projects that adversely affect indigenous rights 
- Indigenous communities are trained on technical diversification of monoculture and agricultural sustainable production. 
- CIMI Tefe builds partnerships with funding agencies and accesses new resources, investing in educators&#x2019; training and expanding the team&apos;s actions.</narrative>
  </description>
